VALUES
(44, 18, 1, 46, 1, 2, 2, 'Paul departed from Athens, and came to Corinth', 'Connection Between Paul and Corinth', 'This connection highlights Paul''s journey to Corinth, where he later addresses the church in his letter. Both passages emphasize the significance of Corinth in Paul''s ministry.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 1, 55, 4, 20, 20, 'Corinth', 'Connection Between Corinth References', 'This connection highlights the continuity of Paul''s ministry in Corinth, as both passages mention the location. Acts 18:1 introduces Paul''s arrival in Corinth, while 2 Timothy 4:20 references Erastus, who remained there, indicating ongoing relationships and activities in the same city.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 1, 44, 19, 1, 1, 'Paul departed from Athens, and came to Corinth', 'Paul''s Journey to Ephesus', 'This connection highlights Paul''s movement between cities, first arriving in Corinth and later traveling to Ephesus. Both passages emphasize the continuity of Paul''s missionary work as he moves from one significant location to another.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 1, 47, 1, 1, 1, 'Paul departed from Athens, and came to Corinth', 'Paul''s Mission to Corinth', 'This connection highlights Paul''s journey to Corinth, where he later addresses the church in his letter. Both passages emphasize Paul''s role in establishing and nurturing the Christian community in Corinth.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 1, 44, 17, 15, 15, 'departed from Athens', 'Paul''s Journey to Corinth', 'This connection highlights Paul''s movement from Athens to Corinth. Both passages emphasize the progression of Paul''s missionary journey.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 1, 47, 1, 23, 23, 'came to Corinth', 'Paul''s Journey to Corinth', 'This connection highlights Paul''s movement to Corinth in both passages. Acts 18:1 mentions his arrival in Corinth, while 2 Corinthians 1:23 reflects on his decision regarding visiting Corinth.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 2, 45, 16, 3, 4, NULL, 'Connection of Priscilla and Aquila', 'This connection highlights the relationship between Priscilla and Aquila in both passages. Acts introduces them as companions of Paul, while Romans acknowledges their significant support and sacrifice for him.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 2, 46, 16, 19, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Aquila and Priscilla', 'This connection highlights the presence of Aquila and Priscilla in both passages. They are mentioned in Acts as having come from Rome and later greet the church in 1 Corinthians, indicating their ongoing role in the early Christian community.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 2, 55, 4, 19, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Aquila and Priscilla', 'This connection highlights the continuity of Aquila and Priscilla''s presence in the early church. Both passages emphasize their significance as a couple in the ministry, linking them across different contexts.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 2, 44, 11, 28, 28, 'Claudius had commanded all Jews to depart from Rome', 'Claudius and Jewish Expulsion', 'Both passages emphasize the reign of Claudius, linking his decree affecting Jews in Rome to the prophecy of a famine during his rule. This connection highlights the impact of Claudius''s actions on the early Christian community.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 2, 44, 18, 26, 26, NULL, 'Connection of Aquila and Priscilla', 'This connection highlights the role of Aquila and Priscilla in the early church. Both passages emphasize their involvement in teaching and supporting fellow believers.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 2, 60, 1, 1, 1, 'born in Pontus', 'Connection of Aquila and Pontus', 'This connection highlights the geographical link between Aquila, who was born in Pontus, and the recipients of Peter''s letter, who are also from Pontus. Both passages emphasize the dispersion of Jews and early Christians across regions, indicating a shared cultural and social context.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 3, 46, 4, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection of Labor and Suffering', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of laboring with one''s own hands. Acts 18:3 highlights the occupation of tentmaking, while 1 Corinthians 4:12 speaks of working with our own hands amidst persecution.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 3, 52, 2, 9, 9, NULL, 'Connection of Labor and Preaching', 'This connection highlights the theme of labor in both passages. Acts 18:3 mentions tentmaking as a profession, while 1 Thessalonians 2:9 emphasizes laboring night and day in preaching.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 3, 47, 11, 7, 7, 'for by their occupation they were tentmakers', 'Connection of Labor and Ministry', 'This connection highlights the theme of labor in both passages. In Acts, Paul works as a tentmaker, while in 2 Corinthians, he emphasizes preaching the gospel freely, suggesting a contrast between his physical labor and spiritual service.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 3, 53, 3, 8, 9, 'wrought', 'Work Ethic in Ministry', 'This connection highlights the theme of labor and self-sufficiency in ministry. Both passages emphasize the importance of working diligently, as seen in ''wrought'' and ''labour and travail''.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 3, 47, 12, 13, 13, 'for by their occupation they were tentmakers', 'Connection of Labor and Burden', 'This connection highlights the theme of labor and self-sufficiency. In Acts, Paul works as a tentmaker, while in 2 Corinthians, he emphasizes not being a burden to the church, suggesting a parallel in his approach to ministry and work.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 3, 44, 20, 34, 35, 'wrought: for by their occupation', 'Labor and Generosity Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the value of labor and supporting others. Acts 18:3 mentions tentmaking, while Acts 20:34-35 highlights ministering to needs and the blessing of giving.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 3, 46, 9, 6, 12, 'by their occupation they were tentmakers', 'Work and Spiritual Labor Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of labor in both passages, where Paul discusses the right to receive support for spiritual work in 1 Corinthians, paralleling his own experience as a tentmaker in Acts. Both emphasize the importance of being compensated for one''s labor, whether in physical or spiritual contexts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 4, 47, 5, 11, 11, 'persuaded the Jews and the Greeks', 'Persuasion in Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the act of persuading others, whether in the synagogue or in the broader context of faith. This connection highlights the importance of reasoning and convincing others about spiritual truths.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 4, 44, 17, 17, 17, 'reasoned in the synagogue', 'Reasoning in the Synagogue', 'Both passages emphasize the act of reasoning and disputing in the synagogue, highlighting the engagement with Jews and devout persons. This connection illustrates the consistent approach of the speaker in addressing both groups during their ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 4, 44, 28, 23, 23, 'persuaded the Jews and the Greeks', 'Persuasion in the Synagogue', 'Both passages emphasize the act of persuading others about Jesus and the kingdom of God. In Acts 18:4, the focus is on reasoning in the synagogue, while Acts 28:23 highlights expounding from the law and prophets.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 4, 14, 32, 11, 11, 'persuaded the Jews and the Greeks', 'Persuasion in Crisis Contexts', 'This connection highlights the theme of persuasion in both passages. In Acts, Paul persuades Jews and Greeks, while in 2 Chronicles, Hezekiah persuades people regarding their faith in God during a crisis.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 4, 42, 4, 16, 16, 'every sabbath', 'Sabbath Synagogue Practices', 'Both passages emphasize the practice of attending the synagogue on the Sabbath. Acts 18:4 describes reasoning in the synagogue every Sabbath, while Luke 4:16 highlights Jesus'' custom of going into the synagogue on that day.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 4, 42, 16, 31, 31, 'persuaded', 'Persuasion in Faith Contexts', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of persuasion in relation to faith. In Acts, the act of reasoning and persuading is highlighted, while in Luke, the inability to be persuaded despite miraculous signs is noted.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 4, 1, 9, 27, 27, NULL, 'Connection of Expansion and Influence', 'This connection highlights the theme of influence and expansion. In Acts, the persuasion of Jews and Greeks suggests a broadening of faith, while Genesis speaks of Japheth''s enlargement and dwelling among Shem, indicating a similar theme of growth and interaction among peoples.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 5, 47, 5, 14, 14, 'pressed in the spirit', 'Love and Testimony Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of being compelled by a higher purpose. In Acts, Paul is ''pressed in the spirit'' to testify, while in 2 Corinthians, the love of Christ ''constraineth us'' to act. Both passages emphasize a driving force behind their actions.', 'theme', 0.356, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 5, 44, 18, 28, 28, 'testified to the Jews that Jesus was Christ', 'Connection of Jewish Testimony', 'Both passages emphasize the act of testifying to the Jews about Jesus as the Christ. In Acts 18:5, Paul is described as testifying, while in Acts 18:28, another figure is convincing the Jews by showing scriptures.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 5, 44, 9, 22, 22, 'Jesus was Christ', 'Proclamation of Jesus as Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the act of testifying and proving that Jesus is the Christ. In Acts 18:5, Paul testifies to the Jews, while in Acts 9:22, Saul confounds the Jews by proving the same truth.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 5, 26, 3, 14, 14, 'pressed in the spirit', 'Connection of Spiritual Pressures', 'This connection highlights the theme of being ''pressed in the spirit'' in Acts and the ''heat of my spirit'' in Ezekiel. Both passages emphasize the intense emotional and spiritual experiences of the individuals as they respond to divine prompting.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 5, 18, 32, 18, 20, 'pressed in the spirit', 'Connection of Constrained Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of being compelled by the spirit to speak. In Acts, Paul is ''pressed in the spirit,'' while in Job, the speaker states, ''the spirit within me constraineth me.'' This connection highlights the urgency and necessity of expressing one''s message.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 5, 24, 6, 11, 11, 'pressed in the spirit', 'Divine Urgency in Proclamation', 'This connection highlights the urgency in both passages. In Acts, Paul is ''pressed in the spirit'' to testify, paralleling Jeremiah''s expression of being ''full of the fury of the Lord'' and weary of restraint.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 5, 24, 20, 9, 9, 'pressed in the spirit', 'Connection of Inner Compulsion', 'Both passages emphasize an inner compulsion to speak. In Acts, Paul is ''pressed in the spirit,'' while Jeremiah describes God''s word as ''a burning fire shut up in my bones.'' This connection highlights the urgency and necessity felt by both figures to proclaim their messages.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 6, 26, 33, 4, 4, 'Your blood be upon your own heads', 'Responsibility for One''s Actions', 'Both passages emphasize personal accountability for one''s choices. In Acts, Paul declares that the consequences of rejection are on the listeners, similar to Ezekiel''s warning about the consequences of ignoring the trumpet''s sound.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 6, 10, 1, 16, 16, 'Your blood be upon your own heads', 'Responsibility for Bloodshed', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of accountability for one''s actions, specifically regarding bloodshed. In each case, the speaker declares that the responsibility for blood lies with the one who has acted against God''s anointed.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 6, 26, 18, 13, 13, 'Your blood be upon your own heads', 'Responsibility for Bloodshed', 'This connection highlights the theme of personal responsibility for one''s actions. Both passages emphasize that the consequences of wrongdoing, symbolized by blood, rest upon the individual who commits the acts.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 6, 16, 5, 13, 13, NULL, 'Shaking as a Symbol of Judgment', 'This connection highlights the act of shaking as a symbol of judgment and separation from those who oppose God''s will. Both passages emphasize a physical gesture of shaking to signify a serious consequence for disobedience.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 6, 44, 13, 51, 51, NULL, 'Rejection and Moving On', 'This connection highlights the act of shaking off dust as a symbolic gesture of rejecting those who oppose the message. Both passages emphasize the response of the apostles to opposition, indicating a shift in focus from the resistant audience to others who may accept their message.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 6, 60, 4, 4, 4, NULL, 'Rejection and Opposition', 'This connection highlights the theme of opposition faced by believers. In Acts, Paul declares his separation from those who oppose him, while in 1 Peter, believers are warned about being spoken evil of by those who continue in their sinful ways.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 6, 42, 9, 5, 5, NULL, 'Rejection and Accountability', 'This connection highlights the theme of accountability for rejecting the message. Both passages emphasize the act of shaking off dust or garments as a testimony against those who oppose the message.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 7, 44, 16, 14, 14, 'worshipped God', 'Worshippers of God', 'This connection highlights the theme of individuals who worship God, as seen in both passages. Justus and Lydia are both described as worshippers, indicating a shared spiritual openness that leads to their engagement with Paul.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 7, 51, 4, 11, 11, 'Justus', 'Connection of Justus in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the presence of Justus in both passages, indicating his significance as a worshipper of God and a fellow worker in the kingdom. Both references emphasize the role of Justus in the early Christian community.', 'keyword', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 7, 44, 10, 2, 2, 'worshipped God', 'Devout Worshippers of God', 'This connection highlights the theme of devout individuals who worship God and have a household influence. Both Justus and the man in Acts 10 are described as worshippers of God, indicating a shared characteristic of piety and devotion.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 7, 44, 13, 42, 42, 'worshipped God', 'Connection Between Synagogue and Gentiles', 'This connection highlights the relationship between the synagogue and Gentile worshippers. In both passages, the presence of Gentiles seeking to learn about God is emphasized, showing a continuity in the outreach to non-Jews.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 7, 44, 17, 4, 4, 'worshipped God', 'Connection of Believers and Worshippers', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of devout individuals who are receptive to the message of God. In Acts 18:7, Justus is noted as a worshipper of God, while Acts 17:4 mentions devout Greeks who believed.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 8, 46, 1, 13, 17, 'believed on the Lord with all his house', 'Baptism and Belief Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of baptism and belief in Christ. Crispus is mentioned in both contexts, highlighting his significance in the early church''s growth.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 8, 41, 16, 15, 16, NULL, 'Belief and Baptism Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief leading to baptism. Both passages emphasize that belief in the Lord is essential for salvation, as seen in Crispus''s belief and the directive to preach and baptize in Mark.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 8, 45, 10, 14, 17, 'believed on the Lord', 'Faith Through Hearing', 'This connection highlights the process of belief and faith. In Acts, Crispus and others believed after hearing the message, paralleling Romans, which emphasizes that faith comes by hearing the word of God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 8, 44, 11, 14, 14, NULL, 'Salvation of Households', 'Both passages emphasize the belief and salvation of entire households. Acts 18:8 mentions Crispus and his house believing, while Acts 11:14 speaks of words for the salvation of ''all thy house.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 8, 44, 8, 12, 12, NULL, 'Belief and Baptism Connection', 'Both passages emphasize belief leading to baptism. In Acts 18:8, Crispus and many Corinthians believed and were baptized, while Acts 8:12 describes men and women who believed and were baptized after Philip''s preaching.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 8, 1, 17, 27, 27, 'with all his house', 'Household Belief and Inclusion', 'This connection highlights the theme of household faith, as both passages emphasize the belief and inclusion of entire households in their respective faith practices. Crispus and his household''s belief parallels the circumcision of Abraham''s household, indicating a communal aspect of faith.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 8, 1, 18, 19, 19, 'his house; and many of the Corinthians', 'Household Faithfulness', 'This connection highlights the importance of household belief in both passages. Crispus''s faith and his household''s belief parallel Abraham''s command to his household to follow the Lord.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 9, 44, 23, 11, 11, 'Be not afraid, but speak', 'Encouragement in Times of Fear', 'Both passages emphasize the Lord''s reassurance to Paul during challenging times. In Acts 18:9, Paul is told not to be afraid, while in Acts 23:11, he is encouraged to be of good cheer, highlighting God''s continual support.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 9, 49, 6, 19, 20, NULL, 'Boldness in Speaking the Gospel', 'This connection highlights the theme of boldness in proclaiming the gospel. Both passages emphasize the encouragement to speak without fear and to communicate the message of Christ confidently.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 9, 26, 2, 6, 8, 'be not afraid', 'Fearlessness in Prophetic Call', 'This connection highlights the theme of fearlessness in the face of opposition. Both passages encourage the speaker to not be afraid and to deliver God''s message despite potential hostility from their audience.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 9, 44, 27, 23, 25, 'Be not afraid', 'Divine Assurance in Adversity', 'Both passages emphasize God''s reassurance to Paul in times of fear. In Acts 18:9, God tells Paul, ''Be not afraid,'' while in Acts 27:24, an angel reiterates, ''Fear not, Paul.''', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 9, 24, 1, 17, 17, 'be not afraid', 'Encouragement to Speak Boldly', 'Both passages emphasize the command to speak without fear. In Acts, Paul is told to ''be not afraid,'' while Jeremiah is instructed to ''be not dismayed.'' This connection highlights a shared theme of divine encouragement in the face of opposition.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 9, 33, 3, 8, 8, 'Be not afraid, but speak', 'Encouragement to Speak Boldly', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine empowerment for speaking truth. Both passages emphasize the importance of declaring God''s message without fear, as seen in Paul''s vision and Micah''s declaration of judgment.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 9, 47, 12, 1, 3, 'speak, and hold not thy peace', 'Visions and Revelations Connection', 'Both passages emphasize divine communication through visions. Acts 18:9 shows the Lord speaking to Paul, while 2 Corinthians 12:1 mentions coming to visions and revelations of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 10, 47, 12, 9, 9, 'I am with thee', 'Divine Presence and Strength', 'This connection highlights the assurance of God''s presence and support in both passages. Acts 18:10 emphasizes God''s protection, while 2 Corinthians 12:9 speaks to the sufficiency of God''s grace and strength in weakness.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 10, 2, 4, 12, 12, 'I am with thee', 'Divine Presence and Assurance', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s assurance of presence. Both passages emphasize that God will be with the individual, providing support and guidance in their mission.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 10, 23, 41, 10, 10, 'I am with thee', 'Divine Presence and Assurance', 'Both passages emphasize God''s promise of presence and support. The phrase ''I am with thee'' in both verses highlights God''s assurance to His people during times of fear and uncertainty.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 10, 40, 28, 20, 20, 'I am with thee', 'Presence of God in Ministry', 'This connection highlights the assurance of God''s presence in both passages. Acts 18:10 states, ''I am with thee,'' while Matthew 28:20 emphasizes, ''I am with you alway.''', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 10, 43, 10, 16, 16, 'I am with thee', 'Divine Presence and Community', 'This connection highlights the assurance of divine presence in both passages. Acts 18:10 emphasizes God''s protection and presence among ''much people,'' while John 10:16 speaks of gathering ''other sheep'' into one fold, suggesting a communal aspect under divine guidance.', 'theme', 0.37, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 10, 45, 8, 31, 31, 'for I am with thee', 'God''s Protection and Presence', 'Both passages emphasize God''s protective presence. Acts 18:10 assures that God is with Paul, while Romans 8:31 declares that if God is for us, no one can oppose us.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 10, 55, 4, 22, 22, 'I am with thee', 'Presence of the Lord', 'This connection highlights the assurance of the Lord''s presence in both passages. Acts 18:10 emphasizes God''s promise of being with Paul, while 2 Timothy 4:22 invokes the presence of the Lord Jesus Christ with Timothy''s spirit.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 11, 44, 14, 3, 3, 'teaching the word of God', 'Teaching and Boldness in Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the act of teaching and speaking boldly about the word of God. Acts 18:11 mentions teaching the word of God, while Acts 14:3 highlights speaking boldly in the Lord, suggesting a shared theme of proclaiming God''s message.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 11, 44, 19, 10, 10, 'teaching the word of God', 'Duration of Teaching Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the length of time spent teaching the word of God. Acts 18:11 mentions a year and six months, while Acts 19:10 states two years, highlighting a sustained effort in spreading the message.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 11, 44, 20, 31, 31, NULL, 'Duration of Teaching Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the length of Paul''s teaching ministry, with Acts 18:11 noting a year and six months and Acts 20:31 referencing three years. This connection highlights Paul''s commitment to teaching and warning the believers over an extended period.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 12, 44, 13, 7, 7, NULL, 'Deputies in Paul’s Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the role of deputies in Paul’s ministry. In Acts 13:7, Sergius Paulus, a deputy, seeks to hear the word of God, while in Acts 18:12, Gallio, another deputy, is involved in a legal matter concerning Paul.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 12, 44, 13, 50, 50, 'made insurrection with one accord', 'Persecution Against Paul', 'Both passages emphasize the coordinated efforts of the Jews to oppose Paul. In Acts 18:12, they act ''with one accord'' to bring him to judgment, while in Acts 13:50, they stir up others to expel Paul and Barnabas.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 12, 40, 27, 19, 19, 'judgment seat', 'Judgment Seat Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a ''judgment seat'' where significant decisions are made regarding individuals. In Acts, Paul is brought before Gallio''s judgment seat, while in Matthew, the judgment seat is where Pilate receives a warning about Jesus. This connection highlights the theme of judicial authority in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 12, 45, 15, 26, 26, 'Achaia', 'Connection Between Achaia References', 'This connection highlights the mention of Achaia in both passages. In Acts, Achaia is the location of Paul''s trial, while in Romans, it is noted as a region contributing to the poor saints in Jerusalem.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 12, 46, 16, 15, 15, 'Achaia', 'Connection between Achaia and ministry', 'This connection highlights the geographical link between Achaia, where Gallio served as deputy, and the house of Stephanas, noted for their ministry. Both passages emphasize the significance of Achaia in the early Christian community.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 12, 47, 1, 1, 1, 'Achaia', 'Connection between Paul and Achaia', 'This connection highlights Paul''s ministry in Achaia, where he faced opposition from the Jews in Acts. Both passages emphasize the significance of Corinth and Achaia in Paul''s apostolic work.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 12, 47, 9, 2, 2, 'Achaia', 'Connection between Achaia and readiness', 'This connection highlights the mention of Achaia in both passages, linking Paul''s experience in Acts with the readiness of the Corinthians in 2 Corinthians. Both passages emphasize the significance of Achaia in the context of communal response and support.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 13, 44, 25, 8, 8, 'worship God contrary to the law', 'Legal Defense in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize the defense of Paul against accusations of violating the law. In Acts 18:13, he is accused of persuading men contrary to the law, while in Acts 25:8, he asserts that he has not offended against the law of the Jews.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 13, 44, 6, 13, 13, 'worship God contrary to the law', 'Accusations Against Believers', 'Both passages emphasize accusations made against individuals for speaking contrary to the law. Acts 18:13 refers to persuading men to worship God contrary to the law, while Acts 6:13 mentions blasphemous words against the law.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
